# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web2py-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] A **database abstraction layer** (**DBAL** or **DAL**) is an application programming interface which unifies the communication between a computer application and databases such as SQL Server, IBM Db2, MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle or SQLite.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Traditionally, all database vendors provide their own interface that is tailored to their products.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] It is up to the application programmer to implement code for the database interfaces that will be supported by the application.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Database abstraction layers reduce the amount of work by providing a consistent API to the developer and hide the database specifics behind this interface as much as possible.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] There exist many abstraction layers with different interfaces in numerous programming languages.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] If an application has such a layer built in, it is called **database-agnostic**.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] The lowest level connects to the database and performs the actual operations required by the users.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] At this level the conceptual instruction has been translated into multiple instructions that the database understands.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Executing the instructions in the correct order allows the DAL to perform the conceptual instruction.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Implementation of the physical layer may use database-specific APIs or use the underlying language standard database access technology and the database's version SQL.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Implementation of data types and operations are the most database-specific at this level.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] The conceptual level consolidates external concepts and instructions into an intermediate data structure that can be devolved into physical instructions.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] This layer is the most complex as it spans the external and physical levels.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Additionally it needs to span all the supported databases and their quirks, APIs, and problems.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] This level is aware of the differences between the databases and able to construct an execution path of operations in all cases.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] However the conceptual layer defers to the physical layer for the actual implementation of each individual operation.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] The external level is exposed to users and developers and supplies a consistent pattern for performing database operations.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Database operations are represented only loosely as SQL or even database access at this level.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Every database should be treated equally at this level with no apparent difference despite varying physical data types and operations.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Libraries unify access to databases by providing a single low-level programming interface to the application developer.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Their advantages are most often speed and flexibility because they are not tied to a specific query language (subset) and only have to implement a thin layer to reach their goal.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] As all SQL dialects are similar to one another, application developers can use all the language features, possibly providing configurable elements for database-specific cases, such as typically user-IDs and credentials.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] A thin-layer allows the same queries and statements to run on a variety of database products with negligible overhead.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Popular use for database abstraction layers are among object-oriented programming languages, which are similar to API-level abstraction layers.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] In an object-oriented language like C++ or Java, a database can be represented through an object, whose methods and members (or the equivalent thereof in other programming languages) represent various functionalities of the database.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] They also share advantages and disadvantages with API-level interfaces.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] An example of a database abstraction layer on the language level would be ODBC that is a platform-independent implementation of a database abstraction layer.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] The user installs specific driver software, through which ODBC can communicate with a database or set of databases.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] The user then has the ability to have programs communicate with ODBC, which then relays the results back and forth between the user programs and the database.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] The downside of this abstraction level is the increased overhead to transform statements into constructs understood by the target database.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Alternatively, there are thin wrappers, often described as *lightweight* abstraction layers, such as OpenDBX and libzdb.
[src:web2py-framework/database-abstraction-layer] Finally, large projects may develop their own libraries, such as, for example, libgda for GNOME.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] "**Don't repeat yourself**" (**DRY**) is a principle of software development aimed at reducing repetition of information which is likely to change, replacing it with abstractions that are less likely to change, or using data normalization which avoids redundancy in the first place.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] The DRY principle is stated as "Every piece of knowledge must have a single, unambiguous, authoritative representation within a system".
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] The principle has been formulated by Andy Hunt and Dave Thomas in their book *The Pragmatic Programmer*.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] They apply it quite broadly to include database schemas, test plans, the build system, even documentation.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] When the DRY principle is applied successfully, a modification of any single element of a system does not require a change in other logically unrelated elements.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] Additionally, elements that are logically related all change predictably and uniformly, and are thus kept in sync.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] Besides using methods and subroutines in their code, Thomas and Hunt rely on code generators, automatic build systems, and scripting languages to observe the DRY principle across layers.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] A particular case of DRY is the single choice principle.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] It was defined by Bertrand Meyer as: "Whenever a software system must support a set of alternatives, one and only one module in the system should know their exhaustive list." It was applied when designing Eiffel.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] The opposing view to DRY is called WET, a backronym commonly taken to stand for *write everything twice* (alternatively *write every time*, *we enjoy typing* or *waste everyone's time*).
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] WET solutions are common in multi-tiered architectures where a developer may be tasked with, for example, adding a comment field on a form in a web application.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] The text string "comment" might be repeated in the label, the HTML tag, in a read function name, a private variable, database DDL, queries, and so on.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] A DRY approach eliminates that redundancy by using frameworks that reduce or eliminate all those editing tasks except the most important ones, leaving the extensibility of adding new knowledge variables in one place.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] This conceptualization of "WET" as an alternative to "DRY" programming has been around since at least 2002 in the Java world, though it is not known who coined the term.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] Another approach to abstractions is to *avoid hasty abstractions* (AHA).
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] AHA is rooted in the understanding that the deeper the investment engineers have made into abstracting a piece of software, the more they perceive that the cost of that investment can never be recovered (sunk cost fallacy).
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] Thus, engineers tend to continue to iterate on the same abstraction each time the requirement changes.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] AHA programming assumes that both WET and DRY solutions inevitably create software that is rigid and difficult to maintain.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] Instead of starting with an abstraction, or abstracting at a specific number of duplications, software can be more flexible and robust if abstraction is done when it is needed, or, when the duplication itself has become the barrier and it is known how the abstraction needs to function.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] Dodds, it is optimizing for change first, and avoiding premature optimization.
[src:web2py-framework/don-t-repeat-yourself] The term was coined by software engineer Cher Scarlett and the practice was described originally by software engineer and author Sandi Metz as "prefer duplication over the wrong abstraction".
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:web2py-framework/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:web2py-framework/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:web2py-framework/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py was originally designed as a teaching tool with emphasis on ease of use and deployment.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Therefore, it does not have any project-level configuration files.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The design of web2py was inspired by the Ruby on Rails and Django frameworks.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Like these frameworks, web2py focuses on rapid development, favors convention over configuration approach and follows a model–view–controller (MVC) architectural pattern.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py uses the WSGI protocol, the Python-oriented protocol for communication between web server and web applications.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] It also provides handlers for CGI and the FastCGI protocols, and it includes the multi-threaded, SSL-enabled Rocket wsgiserver.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] All development, debugging, testing, maintenance and remote database administration can (optionally) be performed without third-party tools, via a web interface, itself a web2py application.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Internationalization (adding languages and writing translations) can also be performed from this IDE.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Each application has an automatically generated database administrative interface, similar to Django.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The web IDE also includes web-based testing.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Applications can also be created from the command line or developed with other IDEs.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py includes pure Python-based template language, with no indentation requirements and a server-side Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The template system works without web2py.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Joomla 1.x templates can be converted to web2py layouts.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py also includes two markup libraries: the markdown2 text-to-HTML filter, which converts Markdown markup to HTML on the fly; and markmin which is inspired by markdown but supports tables, html5 video/audio and oembed protocol.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] A controller without a view automatically uses a generic view that render the variables returned by the controller, enabling the development of an application's business logic before writing HTML.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The dict() output of an action is automatically rendered in HTML if the page is request with a .html extension, in JSON if the page is requested with a .json extension, in XML if requested with .xml.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] It supports other protocols including jsonp, rss, ics, google maps, etc. and is extensible.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Cron is a mechanism for creating and running recurrent tasks in background.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] It looks for an application-specific crontab file which is in standard crontab format.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Since version 2.3 the use of cron is discouraged since web2py comes with a master/worker scheduler.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Jobs can be defined in models and are scheduled by creating an entry in the database.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Users can start work processes who pickup and execute tasks in background.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The schedule is better than cron because it allows to specify more parameters (start time, stop time, number of repetitions, number of trials in case of error) and do a better job at running within constant resource utilization.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py can compile web applications for distribution in bytecode compiled form, without source code.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Unlike frameworks that use specialized template languages for their views, Web2py can also compile the view code into bytecode, since it is pure Python code.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py is unique in the world of Python web frameworks because models and controllers are executed, not imported.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] They are executed in a single global environment which is initialized at each HTTP request.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The major pro is the ease of development, specifically for rapid prototyping.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Another pro is that all the objects defined within this environment are cleanly reset at each HTTP request and never shared across requests.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] This means the developer does not need to worry about changing the state of an object (for example the readable attribute of a database field) or worry about a change leaking to other concurrent requests or other applications.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] A third advantage is that web2py allows the coexistence of multiple applications under the same instance without conflicts even if they use different versions of the same modules or different modules with the same name.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The main disadvantage of the global environment is that model files and controller files are not modules and the order of execution matters (although it can be specified using conditional models).
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Naming conflict is more likely to occur than in normal Python modules.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Some standard Python development tools may not understand objects defined in models and controllers.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Moreover, developers must be aware that code in models is executed at every request and this may cause a performance penalty.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Nothing in web2py prevents developers from using and importing normal Python modules (model-less approach) and for this purpose web2py provides a thread local object (current) to facilitate access to objects associated to the current request.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Yet, in this case, the developer has to be aware of the same pitfalls that other frameworks incur: changing the state of an object defined in a module may affect other concurrent requests.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] web2py runs on Windows, Windows CE phones, Mac, Unix/Linux, Google App Engine, Amazon EC2, and almost any web hosting via Python 2.7/3.5/3.6/pypy.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The current binary version of web2py (for Windows or Mac) includes Python 2.7, but the source version can be run on 2.7 and 3.5+.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Support for Python 2.6 has been dropped on 2017.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] web2py since v1.64.0 runs unmodified on Java with Jython 2.5, without any known limitation.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] web2py code can run with IronPython on .NET.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The web2py binary will run from a USB drive or a portable hard drive without dependencies, like Portable Python.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py can service requests via HTTP and HTTPS with its built-in Rocket server, with Apache, Lighttpd, Cherokee, Hiawatha, Nginx and almost any other web server through CGI, FastCGI, WSGI, mod_proxy, and/or mod_python.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] While a number of web2py developers use text editors such as Vim, Emacs or TextMate Web2py also has a built-in web-based IDE.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Others prefer more specialized tools providing debugging, refactoring, etc.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The database abstraction layer (DAL) of web2py dynamically and transparently generates SQL queries and runs on multiple compatible database backend without the need for database-specific SQL commands (though SQL commands can be issued explicitly).
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] SQLite is included in Python and is the default web2py database.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] A connection string change allows connection to Firebird, IBM Db2, Informix, Ingres, Microsoft SQL Server, MySQL, Oracle, PostgreSQL, and Google App Engine (GAE) with some caveats.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The DAL is fast, at least comparable with SQLAlchemy and Storm.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] An ORM maps database tables into classes representing logical abstractions from the database layer (e.g., a User class or a PurchaseOrder class), and maps records into instances of those classes.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The DAL instead maps database tables and records into instances of classes representing sets and records instead of higher-level abstractions.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] It has very similar syntax to an ORM but it is faster, and can map almost any SQL expressions into DAL expressions.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The DAL can be used independently of the rest of web2py.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The latest version of the DAL has support for 2D GIS functions with Spatialite and PostGIS.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The current API are experimental because of a possible move to 3D APIs.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] web2py supports database migrations—change the definition of a table and web2py ALTERs the table accordingly.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Migrations are automatic, but can be disabled for any table, and migration is typically disabled when an application is ready for live distribution.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Migrations and migration attempts are logged, documenting the changes.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py code is released under GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL) version 3 as of web2py version 1.91.1.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py code before version 1.91.1 was released under GNU GPL v2.0 with commercial exception.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Various third-party packages distributed with web2py have their own licenses, generally public domain, MIT or BSD-type licenses.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Applications built with web2py are not covered by the LGPL license.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Web2py is copyrighted by Massimo DiPierro.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The web2py trademark is owned by Massimo DiPierro.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] In 2011 InfoWorld ranked web2py highest among the top six Python web frameworks, awarded web2py the Bossie award 2011 for best open source application development software.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] In 2012 web2py won the InfoWorld Technology of the Year award.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The base web2py documentation is The Official web2py Book, by Massimo DiPierro.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The manual is a full web2py application and it's freely available online, in PDF format or printed form.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] Online documentation is linked from the web2py home page, with cookbook, videos, interactive examples, interactive API reference, epydoc s (complete library reference), FAQ, cheat sheet, online tools etc.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The lead developer of web2py is Massimo DiPierro, an associate professor of Computer Science at DePaul University in Chicago.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] As of 2011, the web2py homepage lists over 70 "main contributors".
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The source code for the first public version of web2py was released under GNU GPL v2.0 on 2007-09-27 by Massimo DiPierro as the *Enterprise Web Framework* (EWF).
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The name was changed twice due to name conflicts: EWF v1.7 was followed by Gluon v1.0, and Gluon v1.15 was followed by web2py v1.16.
[src:web2py-framework/web2py] The license was changed to LGPLv3 as of web2py version 1.91.1 on 2010-12-21.
